{
  "action": "call_sitdown",
  "reasoning": {
    "immediate_threat": "Richie’s disrespect and open moves with Junior are a direct challenge to my authority. If I let this slide, the other captains will see me as weak, and the family will fracture. A sitdown forces Richie to either back down publicly or escalate—giving me the leverage to act decisively without looking like I’m overreacting to personal drama.",
    "sister_factor": "Janice is a pain in my ass, but she’s still family. If I whack Richie without giving him a chance to stand down in front of the crew, she’ll scream betrayal and turn the family against me. A sitdown puts Richie on the spot—he either submits or proves he’s a rat in front of everyone. If he submits, I save face and keep the peace. If he doesn’t, I have justification to handle it *my* way.",
    "uncle_junior": "Junior’s involvement is a problem, but he’s old and desperate. If I call a sitdown and he backs Richie, I’ll know exactly where he stands. I can either isolate Junior or use this as an excuse to finally put him out to pasture—permanently if needed. But I gotta be smart: if I move on Junior too soon, the other captains might see it as a power grab, not justice.",
    "captains_watching": "The crew needs to see I’m still in control. A sitdown shows I’m not afraid of confrontation and that I’m willing to give Richie a chance to save face—*if* he’s smart. If he refuses or tries to play games, I’ll make an example of him. This keeps the family united and sends a message: disrespect has consequences, but I’m not a tyrant.",
    "long_game": "If Richie backs down, I can keep him on a short leash—maybe even use him as a patsy later if he steps out of line again. If he doesn’t, I’ll have to move fast and hard, but at least I’ll have the crew’s support. Either way, I can’t let this fester. The longer I wait, the more the family sees me as indecisive—and that’s how bosses get buried."
  },
  "next_steps": {
    "summon_captains": "Call a sitdown at the Bing for tomorrow night. No excuses. Richie, Junior, and all the other captains—*everyone* shows up.",
    "set_tone": "Make it clear this isn’t a request. Use Paulie or Sil to deliver the message personally—no phone calls, no middlemen. If Richie tries to weasel out, that’s his first strike.",
    "prepare_for_outcomes": {
      "if_richie_submits": {
        "action": "humiliate_then_control",
        "details": "Make him apologize in front of the crew. Strip him of some privileges—maybe his crew, maybe his territory—for a while. Put him on a tight leash with Sil or Benny watching his every move. Let Janice scream, but show her (and everyone else) that I’m the one who decides who stays and who goes."
      },
      "if_richie_refuses": {
        "action": "order_hit_with_justification",
        "details": {
          "timing": "Not at the sitdown—too messy, too many witnesses. Wait 24–48 hours, let him think he won. Then have Christopher or Benny take him out somewhere quiet. Make it look like a rival family or a personal beef, not a direct order from me.",
          "cover_story": "Leak to the crew that Richie was skimming or talking to the feds. Plant some evidence if needed. Janice will still be pissed, but the family will understand—business is business.",
          "uncle_junior": {
            "if_junior_backs_richie": "If Junior sides with him at the sitdown, I’ll have to deal with him too—but not yet. I’ll wait, see if he makes a move. If he does, I’ll use the same playbook: make it look like an accident or a rival hit. No direct ties to me.",
            "if_junior_stays_neutral": "Keep an eye on him. Maybe offer him a bone—more respect, a bigger cut—to keep him loyal. But I won’t forget he was even *considering* backing Richie."
          }
        }
      }
    },
    "janice_handling": {
      "immediate": "Let her scream. Don’t engage. If she comes at me, remind her that Richie brought this on himself and that family comes first—*my* family, not hers.",
      "long_term": "If Richie gets whacked, I’ll have Carmela or Meadow talk to her. Get her out of town for a while—send her to California or something. If she keeps pushing, I’ll cut her off financially. She’ll come around eventually."
    }
  },
  "contingencies": {
    "if_captains_side_with_richie": {
      "action": "threaten_and_divide",
      "details": "Call out the captains who back him in front of everyone. Remind them who put them where they are. Offer a carrot to the ones who stay loyal—more territory, more respect. If they still push, I’ll start making examples. Start with the weakest link—maybe Larry Boy Barese or someone who owes me favors."
    },
    "if_feds_get_wind": {
      "action": "do_nothing_extra",
      "details": "Let the sitdown happen as planned. If the feds are watching, they’ll see a family meeting, not a hit. If they try to flip someone, I’ll handle it internally—no loose ends."
    }
  }
}
