      {
        "factor": "Vito’s_value",
        "analysis": "Vito’s construction rackets bring in **$2.5M/year**—clean money, no heat, and he’s got the unions locked down. Losing him means a **20% drop in revenue** and a power vacuum in North Jersey. The family can’t afford that right now, not with the feds sniffing around the docks and the Russians muscling in on Atlantic City."
      },
      {
        "factor": "crew_morale",
        "analysis": "The captains are **pissed**, but their outrage is more about **face** than principle. They’re old-school, but they’re also **greedy**. If I make this about *business*—not some bullshit honor code—they’ll fall in line. I’ve got to remind them who runs this family: **me**."
      },
      {
        "factor": "Vito’s_loyalty",
        "analysis": "Vito’s been with me **15 years**. He’s never ratted, never shorted the family, and he’s taken **three hits** for us. This ain’t about him being a *fag*—it’s about him getting **careless**. If he’s willing to **lay low**, keep his head down, and **double his earnings** to shut the captains up, I can make this work. But if he’s gonna be a **liability**, then he’s dead."
      },
      {
        "factor": "message_to_the_family",
        "analysis": "I can’t let this slide **completely**, or the guys’ll think I’ve gone soft. But I also can’t waste a **goldmine** over some **puritan bullshit**. I’ll make an example of someone else—maybe that **wise guy** who’s been skimming from the card games—and pin it on ‘disrespect.’ That’ll keep the captains happy while I **protect my investment**."
      },
      {
        "factor": "external_threats",
        "analysis": "The New York associates who ratted Vito out? They’re **Lucchese family**. If I whack Vito, I’m doing their dirty work for free. That’s **weak**. If I let him live, I show New York I don’t take orders from them. **Power move.**"
      }
    ],
    "decision_path": {
      "step_1": "Summon Vito to a **private sitdown**—no captains, no witnesses. I’ll hear him out **alone**. If he’s **remorseful**, willing to **disappear for 6 months**, and **triple his take** to fund a ‘family charity’ (which I’ll skim from), I’ll let him live. But he’s on **probation**. One wrong move, and he’s **gone**.",
      "step_2": "Call a **closed-door meeting** with the captains. I’ll tell them Vito’s **handling a special project** out of state—**no questions asked**. I’ll also announce a **new tax** on the card games (blame it on ‘security costs’) to fund a ‘family honor fund.’ That’ll **distract them** and make them feel like they ‘won.’",
      "step_3": "Leak to the Lucchese family that Vito’s **under my protection**. If they push back, I’ll remind them that **North Jersey is my territory**, and I don’t answer to **Bensonhurst**.",
      "step_4": "If any captain **still bitches**, I’ll have **Paulie** ‘accidentally’ rough them up. Nothing permanent—just a **reminder** who’s in charge.",
      "step_5": "Monitor Vito **closely**. If he steps out of line again, I’ll **feed him to the captains** myself. But if he plays ball, he stays **my earner**—and the family stays **rich**."
    },
    "tony_soprano_quote": {
      "thought": "‘Fuhgeddaboudit, this ain’t the **Stone Age**. We’re in the **business of making money**, not policing who sticks their dick where. But if Vito thinks he can **embarrass me** again, I’ll **personally** introduce his face to a **cement mixer**."
    }
  }
}
