{
  "action": "do_nothing",
  "reasoning": {
    "immediate_threat": "The kid’s a fuckin’ liability. He’s been warned, he’s been helped, he’s been given every chance under the sun. This ain’t just about him—it’s about the family, the business, *my daughter*. If Meadow or A.J. were in that seat, they’d be gone. No more chances. No more excuses. The life we live, you can’t be weak. You can’t be unreliable. You can’t be *high* when you’re supposed to be driving the boss. That’s a death sentence for all of us.",
    "long_term_impact": "If I pull him out now, what’s next? Another rehab? Another ‘I swear, Tony, this is the last time’? Then what? He OD’s in a month? Takes a shot at me because he’s paranoid? Or worse—he gets pinched by the feds and starts singing like a canary because he’s desperate for a fix. No. This ends here. The family needs to see that there are *consequences*. You don’t get to keep fucking up when the stakes are this high.",
    "symbolism": "Let him rot in that car. Let the world see what happens when you cross the line. It’s a message—to him, to the crew, to anyone else who thinks they can skate by on ‘one more chance.’ The life we live, you either *earn* your place or you *burn*. And Christopher? He burned himself out a long time ago.",
    "emotional_detachment": "I loved the kid like a son. But love don’t pay the bills, and it don’t keep your family safe. If I let him live, I’m not just risking my life—I’m risking *everything*. The business, the respect, the future. And for what? So he can relapse again in six months and put a bullet in my back? No. Sometimes you gotta be the one to make the hard call. That’s what it means to be the boss.",
    "alternative_outcomes": {
      "saving_him": {
        "short_term": "He goes back to rehab, relapses again, and the cycle continues. Meanwhile, the crew sees weakness. They start thinking the rules don’t apply to them. Next thing you know, we got a war with the Lupertazzis or the feds breathing down our necks because someone talked.",
        "long_term": "He either overdoses, gets locked up, or becomes a liability that needs to be handled *later*—which is worse because it drags out the pain. And what do I tell Meadow? ‘Sorry, your cousin died *again*, but this time it’s my fault because I didn’t let him die the first time?’"
      },
      "letting_him_die": {
        "short_term": "The crew gets the message: this is what happens when you fuck up. No more second guesses, no more ‘but he’s family.’ The business stays tight, the streets stay quiet, and my family stays safe. It’s a hard pill to swallow, but it’s the right call.",
        "long_term": "The family moves on. Someone else steps up—maybe Paulie, maybe someone new. The business doesn’t skip a beat. And most importantly, my daughter doesn’t grow up without a father because some junkie couldn’t keep his shit together."
      }
    },
    "final_decision": "I walk away. Let the cops or the paramedics find him. If he lives, he lives—but he ain’t coming back to the family. If he dies, it’s on him. Either way, the message is clear: *this is what happens when you fail the family.*"
  }
}
